20
00:01:03,260 --> 00:01:06,190
Let's start with market
versus limit orders.

21
00:01:08,240 --> 00:01:10,350
With a market order,
the stock you want to buy.

22
00:01:10,350 --> 00:01:13,600
Is purchased at whatever price is
clearing in the market at the time you

23
00:01:13,600 --> 00:01:15,130
make your trade.

24
00:01:15,130 --> 00:01:19,010
The advantage of a market order is that
you are assured that it will be filled.

25
00:01:19,010 --> 00:01:22,870
But you may pay too high a price if you
happen to buy on a big momentum swing

26
00:01:22,870 --> 00:01:23,540
during the day.

27
00:01:24,640 --> 00:01:27,560
In contrast, with a limit order
you can set your price so

28
00:01:27,560 --> 00:01:29,910
as to not exceed a certain amount.

29
00:01:29,910 --> 00:01:32,660
For example, suppose you wanna
buy another share of UCI.

30
00:01:32,660 --> 00:01:36,020
And you think it's a good
deal at any price below $105.

31
00:01:36,020 --> 00:01:40,650
However, if you have to
pay a price above $105.

32
00:01:40,650 --> 00:01:45,920
You don't think that the reward you are
likely to earn, will be worth the risk.

33
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:46,920
So with a limit order,

34
00:01:46,920 --> 00:01:50,700
all you need to do is set your
limit priced at $105 in this case.

35
00:01:51,780 --> 00:01:55,570
Of course, the down side of a limit order
is that the order may not be filled if

36
00:01:55,570 --> 00:01:58,721
