42
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:17,200
But despite all your careful research,
the stock might actually fall.

43
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:21,070
And if it falls a lot, you can lose a lot
of money, and sometimes very quickly.

44
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:25,120
The idea of a stop loss is
to put in a sell order.

45
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:28,370
So that if your stock falls
below a certain amount.

46
00:02:28,370 --> 00:02:30,990
Then the stock is automatically sold.

47
00:02:30,990 --> 00:02:34,720
A good rule here is to never
lose more than 10% in a stock.

48
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:37,825
So for example,
if you buy a share of UCI at $100,

49
00:02:37,825 --> 00:02:40,990
you might wanna put in
a stop loss order for $90.

50
00:02:40,990 --> 00:02:47,010
And here's a cool related concept,
that of the trailing stop loss.

51
00:02:47,010 --> 00:02:50,180
The idea here is to never
turn a winner into a loser.

52
00:02:50,180 --> 00:02:55,310
So for example if you buy UCI at $100 and
it goes to $110.

53
00:02:55,310 --> 00:02:59,760
The wise thing to do here might be to
raise your stop loss order to $100

54
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:01,930
rather than the original 90.

55
00:03:01,930 --> 00:03:06,130
So if UCI falls back down,
you at least didn't lose any money and

56
00:03:06,130 --> 00:03:09,090
therefore didn't turn
a winner into a loser.

